FOCUS_TIME_CALENDAR_BLOCKING_RESEARCH_v1.0

=== EXECUTIVE SUMMARY ===
Comprehensive research for implementing Focus Time calendar-based blocking feature in FocusFlow desktop app (Tauri + React).

=== 1. CALENDAR EVENT DETECTION ===

RECOMMENDATION: Dual approach - Title prefix (primary) + Extended properties (secondary)

PRIMARY: Title Prefix Approach
- Recommended prefixes: [Focus], Focus:, Focus Time:
- Case-insensitive parsing
- Regex patterns: ^\\[focus\\], ^focus:, ^focus time:
- PROS: User-friendly, works with any calendar client, no special permissions, visible and self-documenting
- CONS: User must remember prefix, slightly clutters titles

SECONDARY: Extended Properties (for advanced users)
- Property key: focusflow_type = focus_time
- Additional props: focusflow_allowed_apps (JSON), focusflow_strictness (soft|medium|hard)
- Namespace: private (per-attendee)
- PROS: Clean titles, structured data, can store complex configs
- CONS: Requires FocusFlow to create events, not portable

NOT RECOMMENDED: Color-based detection
- colorId is per-attendee, often null, unreliable across views

FALLBACK: Description patterns
- Detect: Allowed apps:, Focus mode:, Block all except:

=== 2. ALLOWED APPS FORMAT ===

RECOMMENDATION: Hybrid inline + predefined groups

INLINE FORMAT (in event description):
- Format: Allowed: app1, app2, app3
- Examples: Allowed: vscode, terminal, slack
- Line prefix detection, comma-delimited, case-insensitive

PREDEFINED APP GROUPS:
- @coding-tools: VSCode, Code, IntelliJ, Xcode, Terminal, iTerm, Warp, WebStorm, PyCharm, Cursor
- @communication: Slack, Discord, Teams, Zoom, Messages
- @productivity: Notion, Obsidian, Notes, Bear, Craft, Linear, Jira
- @creative: Figma, Sketch, Photoshop, Illustrator
- @browsers: Safari, Chrome, Firefox, Arc, Brave
- @reference: Preview, Books, Kindle, PDF Expert

GROUP SYNTAX:
- Allowed: @coding-tools, slack
- Allowed: @productivity, @communication

=== 3. APP IDENTIFICATION ===

macOS:
- Primary: Process name (via sysinfo crate - already implemented)
- Secondary: Bundle identifier (via NSRunningApplication)
- MAPPING REQUIRED: User-friendly names to process names

COMMON MAPPINGS (macOS):
- Visual Studio Code / VSCode / VS Code -> Code
- Google Chrome / Chrome -> Google Chrome
- Slack -> Slack
- Discord -> Discord
- Zoom -> zoom.us
- iTerm -> iTerm2
- Microsoft Teams / Teams -> Microsoft Teams
- IntelliJ -> IntelliJ IDEA

Windows:
- Primary: Executable name (normalize by stripping .exe)
- VSCode -> Code.exe -> Code
- Chrome -> chrome.exe -> chrome

DETECTION STRATEGY:
1. Try exact process name match (case-insensitive)
2. Try user-friendly name to process name mapping
3. Try partial/contains match if enabled
4. Fall back to bundle ID lookup

IMPLEMENTATION:
- Store mappings in config file for user customization
- Allow users to add custom mappings
- Auto-detect running apps and learn from selections

=== 4. ENFORCEMENT STRATEGIES ===

RECOMMENDATION: Graduated approach with 3 levels

SOFT MODE (Gentle Reminder):
- Show notification when blocked app opened
- Display focus overlay with session info
- Offer to end session or continue
- Single-click bypass allowed

MEDIUM MODE (Moderate Block):
- Show blocking overlay on app window
- Require typing confirmation to bypass (I need to use this)
- Log bypass attempts for reflection

HARD MODE (Strict Block):
- Terminate blocked processes after 3s grace period
- No bypass during session
- Notification before termination
- Emergency override: end session only

OVERLAY APPROACH (Recommended for soft/medium):
- Create transparent overlay window over blocked app
- Display focus timer and session info
- Non-destructive, reversible, cross-platform

PROCESS TERMINATION (Hard mode only):
- Use existing implementation in process.rs
- Grace period: 3000ms
- Protected processes list already exists
- User-owned processes only

=== 5. EMERGENCY OVERRIDE MECHANISMS ===

END SESSION:
- Trigger: Click End Session button
- Friction: Confirmation dialog
- Effect: Ends focus session, disables all blocking

PAUSE SESSION:
- Trigger: Click Pause button
- Friction: None for first 3 pauses, then requires reason
- Effect: Pauses timer and blocking temporarily

ALLOW ONCE (soft/medium modes):
- Trigger: Type reason or wait 10 seconds
- Effect: Allows specific app for 5 minutes

ALWAYS-ALLOWED DEFAULTS:
- Phone, Messages, FaceTime, Find My
- Password managers (1Password, Passwords app)
- Emergency SOS related apps

=== 6. INTEGRATION POINTS (Existing Codebase) ===

Types to extend:
- /packages/types/src/calendar.ts - Add: is_focus_time, allowed_apps, strictness

Backend files to modify:
- /packages/desktop/src-tauri/src/commands/calendar.rs - Add: detect_focus_time_events()
- /packages/desktop/src-tauri/src/blocking/process.rs - Add: allowlist checking logic
- /packages/desktop/src-tauri/src/commands/focus.rs - Add: calendar-triggered session start

Frontend files to modify:
- /packages/desktop/src/hooks/useCalendar.ts - Add: useFocusTimeEvents()
- /packages/desktop/src/features/Calendar.tsx - Add: Focus Time event display

=== 7. UX RECOMMENDATIONS ===

First-time setup:
- Wizard to create first Focus Time event
- Suggest app groups based on detected profession
- Test blocking with 1-minute session
- Explain override mechanisms

During session:
- Clear visual indicator of focus mode
- Remaining time prominently displayed
- Quick access to allowed apps list
- Log blocked attempts for post-session review

Post-session:
- Summary of blocked attempts
- Celebrate completed sessions
- Suggest adjustments if many bypasses

=== SOURCES ===
- Google Calendar Extended Properties: developers.google.com/workspace/calendar/api/guides/extended-properties
- Google Calendar Colors API: developers.google.com/workspace/calendar/api/v3/reference/colors
- macOS Bundle IDs: support.apple.com/guide/deployment/get-the-bundle-id-for-a-mac-app
- Focus app patterns: blog.pragmaticdx.com/p/how-to-actually-protect-focus-time

Focus Time Feature Security Review - 2026-02-01 | SECURITY: Medium-Bypass via app renaming, DoH bypasses hosts blocking. Low-Nuclear/strict mode not persisted to DB. Good-Input validation, protected processes. | CORRECTNESS: Medium-No overlapping schedule validation, timezone handling implicit, calendar disconnect unhandled. Low-Midnight schedules edge cases. | UX: Medium-Override mechanism unclear, 3s notification grace period short. Low-No fallback mode indicator. | INTEGRATION: Timer sync robust with backend ownership. Mini-timer has local tick fallback. State uses proper Arc<RwLock>. | PLATFORM: macOS needs notarization and Full Disk Access. Windows needs admin. Linux DNS flush incomplete. | MITIGATIONS: Persist nuclear/strict to DB, add schedule overlap detection, show fallback indicator, consider browser extension, add bundle ID matching on macOS, handle token refresh errors, add countdown before termination, document elevation in onboarding.

Implemented React frontend for Calendar-Based Focus Time feature. Created types (focus-time.ts), hooks (useFocusTime.ts), components (AppSelector, FocusTimeOverlay, UI components), and main feature (FocusTime.tsx). Updated Calendar.tsx with Focus Time tab. Requires 3 Radix UI packages: @radix-ui/react-scroll-area, @radix-ui/react-alert-dialog, @radix-ui/react-accordion. Backend Tauri commands need implementation. See FOCUS_TIME_DEPENDENCIES.md for details.

# Calendar-Based Focus Time Backend Implementation Summary

## Overview
Implemented a calendar-based Focus Time feature for the FocusFlow desktop app. This feature allows users to schedule Focus Time blocks in their calendar and have apps automatically blocked during those times using an "inverse blocking" approach - blocking ALL apps EXCEPT those explicitly allowed.

## Files Created/Modified

### New Files

1. **focus_time/mod.rs** (core module)
   - FocusTimeState struct for managing active Focus Time state
   - FocusTimeEventParsed struct for parsed calendar events
   - FocusTimeManager for state management
   - detect_focus_time_events() - scans calendar events for Focus Time blocks
   - find_active_focus_time() - finds currently active Focus Time
   - find_upcoming_focus_times() - finds upcoming Focus Times

2. **focus_time/app_registry.rs** (app name mapping)
   - AppRegistry struct with 40+ app mappings
   - Maps friendly names to process names (e.g., "vscode" -> "Code", "code.exe")
   - macOS bundle identifier mappings
   - 8 predefined categories: @coding, @terminal, @browser, @communication, @writing, @design, @productivity, @music
   - expand_category() - expands categories to process names
   - is_process_allowed() - checks if process is in allowed list

3. **commands/focus_time.rs** (Tauri commands)
   - get_focus_time_events() - get all Focus Time events from calendars (7 days)
   - get_active_focus_time() - get current active Focus Time
   - get_allowed_apps() - get apps allowed in current Focus Time
   - override_focus_time_apps() - add/remove apps during active session
   - end_focus_time_early() - end current Focus Time before calendar end
   - start_focus_time_now() - manually start Focus Time from calendar event
   - is_app_allowed_during_focus_time() - check if specific app is allowed
   - get_focus_time_categories() - get available app categories
   - get_focus_time_common_apps() - get common apps for UI
   - expand_focus_time_categories() - expand categories to apps
   - get_focus_time_status() - comprehensive status including upcoming events
   - sync_focus_time_with_calendar() - auto-activate/deactivate based on calendar

### Modified Files

1. **state.rs**
   - Added focus_time_state: Arc<RwLock<FocusTimeState>> to AppState

2. **lib.rs**
   - Added focus_time module
   - Registered 12 new Tauri commands

3. **commands/mod.rs**
   - Added focus_time module export

4. **blocking/process.rs**
   - Added Focus Time inverse blocking mode
   - When Focus Time is active, blocks ALL apps not in allowed list
   - Focus Time takes priority over standard blocking
   - Grace period warnings before termination
   - Records block attempts as "focus_time_app" type

## Detection Pattern
Calendar events are detected as Focus Time if title contains:
- "focus time", "focus block", "deep work", "focus session"
- "no meetings", "heads down", "do not disturb", "dnd"
- "coding time", "writing time"

Allowed apps are parsed from event description:
- Format: "Allowed: @coding, @terminal, notion"
- Categories start with @ (e.g., @coding, @browser)
- Individual apps listed by name

## App Categories
- @coding: VS Code, JetBrains IDEs, Xcode, vim, etc.
- @terminal: Terminal, iTerm2, Warp, Alacritty, etc.
- @browser: Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Edge, Arc, etc.
- @communication: Slack, Discord, Teams, Zoom, etc.
- @writing: Notion, Obsidian, Word, Bear, etc.
- @design: Figma, Sketch, Photoshop, Illustrator, etc.
- @productivity: Todoist, Things, Linear, Asana, etc.
- @music: Spotify, Apple Music

## Test Results
All 23 unit tests pass covering:
- Focus Time detection (basic, case-insensitive, keywords)
- Category parsing and expansion
- Allowed apps list management
- App registry mappings
- Process name normalization

## Frontend Events Emitted
- focus-time-started: When Focus Time begins (manual or scheduled)
- focus-time-ended: When Focus Time ends (early or scheduled)
